Part 2: Downloading, Processing, and Discussing a Novel Gene in a Continuous Trait from Human Genomic Data on Ensembl (50 points)

So far in our labs, weve been focusing on the human mitochondrial uncoupling protein 1 (UCP1) gene.

    1. According to the readings for Module 1, where is the protein UCP1 primarily expressed? (2 points)
      1. brown adipocytes
      1. cardiac cells
      1. gastrointestinal lining
      1. All of the above


    1. What role does UCP1 normally play in the human body? (2 points)
      1. It regulates androgen levels by lysing testosterone
      1. Modulates a protein called angiotensin II (ANG II) that increases blood pressure and inflammation
      1. It is a transmembrane protein in the inner mitochondrial membrane that uncouples respiration from ATP synthesis, resulting in the breakdown of fatty acids and the release of heat
      1. Appends antigens to the surfaces of blood cells, enabling self/not-self cellular recognition required by immune systems


    1. What is the best way to describe the role of UCP1 in human obesity? (2 points)
      1. UCP1 expression is positively related to body fatness, and so high expression of UCP1 is associated with obesity
      1. Some variants of UCP1 appear to be associated with variation in body fatness and metabolic function, which may be related to its role in fat dissipation within brown adipocytes
      1. UCP1 burns fat, so higher expression of UCP1 is exclusively seen in lean individuals


    1. Traits like body fatness or BMI, in which hundreds of genes contribute incrementally small amounts of variation to the distribution of the phenotype, are called what? (2 points)
      1. Monogenic
      1. Oligogenic
      1. Polygenic
      1. Discrete


    1. Such complex traits often follow a normal distribution. Which of the following are characteristics of the normal distribution? (2 points)
      1. Trait values are distributed symmetrically about the mean
      1. The variance in trait values is the average of the squared difference of each value from the mean
      1. About 68% of the sample is within 1 standard deviation from the mean
      1. It shows high levels of skew


    1. Which of the two foundational scientists weve discussed in this course contributed to how we think about and analyze continuous variation in complex traits, and was the first to characterize the normal distribution? (2 points)
      1. Gregor Mendel
      1. Sir Francis Galton
      1. Charles Darwin
      1. Leslea Hlusko


    1. The basic equation for a regression line is y = mx + b.     1. Which of the above regression parameters is actually representative of the relationship between body mass severity and changes in SNP allele? (2 points)
      1. y
      1. m

    1. If we found a paralog of UCP1, it most likely represents what kind of larger-scale variation in the genome? (2 points)
      1. transposable element
      1. microsatellite
      1. copy number variant (CNV)
      1. variable number of tandem repeats (VNTR)

      1. No

      1. 0
      1. 3
      1. 17
      1. 34


    1. What is the location of FGF9 in the human genome (i.e., on which chromosome, and at what base-pair position does the gene region start and end). Answer in the standard format: [chromosome number]:[start-position]-[end-position]. (3 points)

An Isolated Finnish Population in the Barents Sea

Imagine you meet a small population of Finns on an island in the Barents Sea, which has been isolated from other Finns for generations. When you genotype this population (n = 250), you observe the following genotype frequencies for * rs182718810*:

  • GG = 115

  • GT = 18

  • GA = 76

  • AA = 24

  • TA = 10

  • TT = 7

    1. What is the frequency of the T allele in this population? (0.5 points)

    1. What is the frequency of the G allele in this population? (0.5 points)

    1. If this SNP is in Hardy-Weinberg equilibrium, what is the expected count of TT genotyped individuals in this population? (0.5 points)

    1. If this SNP is in Hardy-Weinberg equilibrium, what is the expected count of GA genotyped individuals in this population? (0.5 points)

    1. What is the Chi-squared value of the observed genotype counts vs.the genotype counts expected under Hardy-Weinberg Equilibrium? (2 points)

    1. What are the degrees of freedom for this test? (1 points)




    1. Using the above table to estimate the P-value of this test, is this SNP in Hardy-Weinberg equilibrium in this relict population? (2 points)

    1. Under the Modern Synthesis definition of evolution, has this relict population evolved since it first split from the Finnish population? (2 points)


    1. If a functional FGF9 protein is necessary to express UCP1, and not having a valine at the 13th animo acid of FGF9 makes it non-functional, what are the possible outcomes for UCP1 function in the relict Finnish population? (2 points)
